      <div class="container">
        <h1 class="display-3">Prodigy: William James Sidis</h1>
        <p>A Remarkable Human Being</p>
        
        <div style="font-size:145%;"> 
          <div class= "col-md-6";>
           <img class="img-responsive" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d3/William_James_Sidis_1914.jpg">William James Sidis at his <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvard_University"target="_blank">Harvard </a>graduation</a>
          </div>
        </div> 
      
        <div class="col-md-4";>
          <p><img class="img-responsive"src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/55/8-cell-simple.gif">The object shown here is the 4D equivalent of a cube, known as a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tesseract"target="_blank">tesseract</a>. William James Sidis was a specialist in the mathematics of 4D bodies.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

 <div class="container">
   <div class="row">
     <div class="col-md-6">
       <h2>Early Life as a Prodigal Genius</h2>
       <ul style="font-size:120%;">
         <li>Capable of reading the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/"target="_blank">New York Times </a>at the age of 18 months.</li>
         <li>By 8 years of age, he taught himself 8 languages (Armenian, French, German, Greek, Hebrew, Latin, Russian and Turkish).</li>
         <li>At age 8 he invented a language he named <a                         href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_James_Sidis#Vendergood_language"target="_blank">Vendergood</a>.</li>
         <li>Was refused entry to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvard_University"target="_blank">Harvard </a> at age 9 due to his young age.</li>
         <li>Entered <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harvard_University"target="_blank">Harvard </a> at the age of eleven.</li>
         <li>At age 12 he gave a lecture on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-dimensional_space"target="_blank">four-dimensional bodies </a>to the Harvard Mathematical Club.
         <li>Was friends with child prodigy <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norbert_Wiener"target="_blank">Norbert Wiener</a>, pioneer of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cybernetics"target="_blank">cybernetics.</a></li>
         <li>Earned his Bachelor of Arts degree, cum laude, on June 18, 1914, at age 16.
         <li>Claimed to speak over 40 languages and dialects.</li>
       </ul>
     </div>
     
     <div class="col-md-6">
       <h2>Teaching, Post-Graduate Work and Writing and Philosophy</h2>
         <ul style="font-size:120%;">
           <li>He served for a brief time at the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/League_of_Nations"target="_blank">League of Nations</a>.</li>
           <li>In 1915, at the age of 17, as a graduate fellow working toward his doctorate at the William Marsh Rice Institute for the Advancement of Letters, Science, and Art (now <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rice_University"target="_blank">Rice University</a>) in Houston, he worked as a mathematics teaching assistant.
           <li>Enrolled at the <a href="http://hls.harvard.edu/"target="_blank">Harvard Law School</a> in September 1916.</li>
           <li>Developed a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Libertarianism"target="_blank">libertarian</a> philosophy based on individual rights and "the American social continuity".</li>
           <li>Noted for numerous writings on many subjects including Cosmology, Anthropology, Philology, and Transportation Systems.</li> 
         </ul>
       
       </div>  
     </div>
   
